    <h1>FRUIT OF ASAM GELUGUR TREE SOLD AS SOURING AGENT</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201212/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-12"><time>2020-12-12</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | DESIGN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>This tree was found grow­ing in a park and its fruit looked like small pump­kins (above). They were left to rot. Is the fruit edi­ble?</p>
    <p>Jack Leong</p>
    <p>The fruit is pro­duced by a tree whose botan­i­cal name is Garcinia atro­viridis. It is com­monly known as Asam gelugur and is a rel­a­tive of the man­gos­teen tree.</p>
    <p>This tree has a rel­a­tively slow grow­ing rate. Its fruit breaks into seg­ments and is very sour and tart. It is dried and sold as a souring agent for lo­cal cur­ries and soups.</p>

